05495nam a22009255i 9781487533670DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814875336707 a10.3138/97814875336702doi  a(DE-B1597)570747  a(OCoLC)1182807630  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB3216.C74 7aREL0400002bisacsh04a296.3/62231 aHollander, Dana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEthics Out of Law :bHermann Cohen and the “Neighbor” /cDana Hollander. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (324 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments and Preface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One Cohen’s “Methodistic” Founding of Ethics in Legal Science: Generation of the Legal Person -- tChapter Two “For the Idea of Law [Gesetz] He Substitutes Morality”: Understanding Law in Cohen’s Ethik, with Help from the Early Strauss -- tChapter Three Philosophico-Political Theology as Method: From Strauss’s Philosophy and Law to Cohen’s “Philosophy of Jewish Religion” -- tChapter Four Isolation and Universalism: Cohen’s New Messianic Politics of Jewish Law -- tChapter Five Against “Affective Expansiveness”: Cohen’s Critique of Stammler’s Theory of “Right Law” -- tChapter Six The “Neighbor” as an Institution of Law (Recht), from the Ethik to the Jewish Writings -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHermann Cohen (1842–1918) was a leading figure in the Neo-Kantian philosophical movement that dominated European thought before 1918. He was also an inaugural figure in modern Jewish philosophy in the twentieth and twenty-first centuries. This book explores Cohen’s striking claim that ethics is rooted in law – a claim developed both in his philosophical ethics and his philosophy of Judaism, in particular in his writings on "love-of-neighbor," up to and including his well-known Religion of Reason. Dana Hollander proposes that neither Cohen’s systematic philosophy nor his "Jewish" philosophy should be seen as the dominant framework for his oeuvre as a whole, but that his understanding of key philosophical questions takes shape in the passages between both corpuses, a trait that could be seen as paradigmatic for modern Jewish philosophy. Ethics Out of Law taps into one of the prime topics of current interest in the field of Jewish philosophy: the nature of Jewish political existence and the changing configurations of "law" that this entails.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aEthicsxPhilosophy. 0aJewish ethicsxPhilosophy. 0aJewish philosophyy19th century. 0aLaw and ethics. 0aLawxPhilosophy. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / General.2bisacsh  aGerman philosophy.  aHermann Cohen.  aJewish philosophy.  aJewish studies.  aKant.  acontinental philosophy.  aethics.  alegal theory.  alove of neighbor.  amodern Jewish thought.  aneo-Kantianism.  aphilosophy of religion.  areason.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021 Englishz978311075419308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2021z9783110753974oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753367040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487533670423Coveruhttps://